And that’s why Eva’s reference to that line makes me rabid in a bad way like get outta here, you hussie!! Just get to the part where you talk about The Boss so she can yet again slam dunk this game like she deserves
That’s what makes Naomi’s speech so important too, about living on. She also holds onto regrets about her brother Gray Fox, and like the members of FOXHOUND, she takes it out on solid snake.

And that’s why Otacon’s ending fucks so hard. He prevents snake from doing the same, from becoming yet another step of the cycle of The Boss and Big Boss’s legacy. Of course the past still chases him via Ocelot and *I guess* Solidus but, at least in mgs1, he learns to live on.

let go of the past now that Big Boss is dead, and their speeches adding to the overarching themes of regret and the inability to move forward. It’s like solid snake is sending ghosts to the afterlife, bc they’re no longer individuals but a single ideal whose era is over.

other mgs games keep unintentionally boosting my love for mgs1 or at least making me better understand why I love it. The stark contrast between mgs3 bosses being weird and just saying their names over in a silly way versus the mgs1 bosses being these people unable to —

@alas_poor IT GOT MY ASS GOOD!! Like, again, she slam dUNKED this game into at least an 8/10 (MGS1 being the 10/10 of course). Exactly everything I wanted, The Ladder is excused, makes it even more worth playing again and will prob rise to a 9/10 which is what I’m shooting (sneaking) for

Def glad I played it with Brian tho bc I needed both motivation & someone to read me the guide lol. Despite loving the challenge of stealth, I’m a sore loser & dying or even just getting caught makes putting the game down for a bit very tempting. Dying twice? Game too hard, bye

nuzlocke myself lol. Like not using the EZ gun will make a hell of a difference I think, but I’ll still have some good camo to make up for it and still focus primarily on the story without worrying about new/unforeseen challenges.

I think I’ll chip away at my mgs3 ng+ during my alone time sometime soon. I would like to see it again now knowing what’s going on and finding things I missed/didn’t think of at the time. Since I can’t change the difficulty but I want all my well-earned gear I’ll have to —

poignant-bullshit sandwich where The Boss was the two slices of bread and everything else was various levels of good, cringe, and insane. I was always in her court and she fucking hit like two slam dunks in this game in the last 30-45 minutes. Milfs never disappoint, confirmed.

monologue where the first half is like the Silent Hill 2 Mary letter bc it’s just as infuriating and long-winded and she says a line from MGS1 that is from a GOOD monologue and I flip my shit. But the second half is all Boss content and I cry, so it was like a —

THEN I have to watch EVA and Snake roll around on the floor for an extended period of time and I physically recoiled in my chair for every second of it. Of course she fucks off afterward bc she’s like a double triple super agent and I’m forced to listen to her —

The ending of mgs3 was such a series of funny emotional whiplash. Like I have to drag EVA around which sucks bc I don’t like her, and then I fight The Boss and it was such a beautiful and special 10 minutes, then Ocelot is there and I’m both confused but pleasantly surprised.

Also loved the Boss as much as I hoped I would. Her tragic loss as a mother (leading to her “adopting” the cobra team) and being a conflicted patriot was *chef’s kiss*. And then her unknowingly being so close to her long lost son AND knowing what his future looks like 😭

Also the sound design continued to absolutely fucking rock. I love turning left and right to pin point the exact direction of an enemy walking from place to place. Would not NEARLY be as good without it.
And getting to do it in my favorite / least frustrating way meant I was able to enjoy the moment so much more and focus on the gravity of the situation 😌🥲

I love how the final fight just lets you handle it however you want. I got to snipe to my heart’s content and I think taking that more slow & precise method while under a time limit made it a personal player experience that also provided a universal challenge.
I hoped that her inevitable monologue would make me upset and it did. Mission accomplished boys, we got another devastating ending under our belts.

out of context, is absolutely devastating *in* context. The conversation with him post-Liquid fight where snake agonizes over not being able to save Meryl and Otacon talks about the reason for living makes me wanna cry (& reply it) just thinking about it, it’s so fucking good.

And then MGS1 😩👌🏻 so many Otacon jokes that, in context, are completely turned on its head for me. The context of “can love bloom even on the battlefield” meme turning it into something so poignant. Literally every conversation with Otacon, a very “butt of the joke” character —
on how he’s vulnerable and — I can’t think of how exactly to word it — all has become clear and the lies can’t hide anymore.

In mgs2 the context of the infamous “naked raiden section” was better in context because it was a part of such a turning point in the narrative as the curtain was pulled away to reveal how raiden’s whole mission is a farce, and him being naked is also a literal metaphor —
beginning the gun fight. He’s constantly trying to prove he can back up his eccentric taste with real power and even changing tactics when snake suggests improvements.

adding to this, I think there are moments that have improved more with context. Like I love Ocelot’s character arc in mgs3 and the infamous gun scene had new meaning as it was more insight into his hubris and desire to prove to snake that he’s better than him before even —
But if you genuinely dislike MGS1’s writing (boss fights I understand) then I curse you. A pox on your house, may your womb be barren, etc etc

breathing room and take that opportunity to explore new ways to create rich narratives with new, unique tones. I really like how each MGS game has different styles and therefore fans all have their own favorite for various reasons. Nobody is wrong for liking one over another.

Part of why MGS1 has such great success (in my heart) I think is how short it is. The limitation in length works to its benefit as it forces the story be condensed, heavy, and each monologue can be given way more attention. The later installments obviously have more —

I also need to be more careful about my expectations tbh. It’s like “yeah it’ll be good, but will it be *MGS1* good?” It’s unintentional and I’m not trying to scrutinize the other MGS games bc they don’t have the exact same tone.

MGS1 gets a pardon for all the nightmare boss fights bc I wanna roll up that game’s script and smoke it it’s so good. MGS2 is kinda middle ground, bc the plot twist was good but none of the Deep Takes really resonated with me and I forgot the ending’s entire context.

The make or break will be the ending. Any media I consume, the ending is what matters most. If I love the ending, I can pardon any groaners or gripes I have with the game. If I hate it, the rating drops a whole 1-3 points (out of 10).

MGS3 still has a lot going for it as a whole. The gameplay is the most satisfying out of the three so far, so much so that I’d definitely play it again without hesitation. It has one of my favorite boss fights in recent memory, and the plot keeps me interested and wanting more.

what the fuck that’s about” and then after I was still asking “but what the fuck was that about?” I’ll still be thinking about it, trying to derive my own meaning from it, but I think its placement in the narrative leaves it at a disadvantage in my personal opinion on it.

Maybe for players going in totally blind, getting to the top of the ladder and going “what the fuck was that?” forces them to reflect and derive their own meaning for the ascent. Though, in my experience where I have prior knowledge, I entered with “boy I wonder —

I don’t find that there’s a particular “catalyst” that calls for the climb to elicit a more emotional reaction. Snake still has the rest of the sons to kill, still has both eyes, he just killed some old guy and now he’s climbing a particularly long ladder to wherever.

Like if it was placed in a similar way in MGS1, it’d be like, after the first boss fight with Ocelot or after you rescue Otacon from Gray Fox. Anything before Meryl’s capture/possible death where it’s just kinda there.

I thought “maybe the reason it is so memorable goes beyond the joke, and in context it is a poignant moment near the very end meant to symbolize Snake’s journey and ascension to becoming Big Boss”. Turns out it really was “haha funny ladder scene”.

I think it would’ve been 100x different if I hadn’t known The Ladder scene for more than a decade in advance. It was always “haha funny ladder scene” and, beginning MGS3 after my experiences with 1&2, I finally began to consider the context in which it might exist.
